Answer: You are looking for a "contrary-to-fact" conditional (C-to-F conditional).

A, B, and D are \em{trivially} true if $R$, while C is \em{trivially} false (C is \em{strongly} true, not just $true$, if $~$R$~$).

I'll refer to the negation of each possibility as $R \Rightarrow a^*$.

With that in mind, note that if $R\Rightarrow a$, then $a^*\Rightarrow a^*\Rightarrow a$ (the conditional always holds), thus:
\begin{itemize}
\item $R\Rightarrow \lnot a^*$.
\item $\lnot R\Rightarrow b_1^*$.
\end{itemize}

Here we see these two statements are logically equivalent - \em{every} proposition is true, or every proposition is false.  This is usually called the Law of Reverse Possibility, and is true when we are given contrary-to-fact conditions and we always assume the contrary-to-fact condition is true for our purposes.

We could make similar argument with the C-to-F conditional:
\begin{itemize}
\item $R\Rightarrow b_2^*$.
\item $b_1^*\Rightarrow b_2^*$.
\item $ab_2^*$.
\item $R\Rightarrow ab_2^*$.
\item $R$.
\item $\lnot R\Rightarrow ab_2^*$.
\item $a\lor b_2^*$.
\end{itemize}

The two statements are logically equivalent when we have the C-to-F conditional.

It's also possible to see this using De Morgan's Laws (if it's even relevant to your proof).  Given the $a^*$ terms, you can write:
\begin{itemize}
\item $R\Leftrightarrow \lnot a^*$.
\item For all $b_i^*$, $R\Leftrightarrow b_i^*$.
\item Therefore, $R\Leftrightarrow \lor a^*$.
\end{itemize}

To make something similar work for C-to-F, note that we have $a\lor b$.  Then we see we can use the previous point to show we have the equivalence $a\lor b\Leftrightarrow R\Leftrightarrow \lor a\lor \lor b$.

Then, it doesn't seem to matter which C-to-F conditional we use, because the statement $R$ is \em{always} true for all the possibilities, we get these equivalences for all of them:
\begin{itemize}
\item $R\Leftrightarrow c_1^*$.
\item $R\Leftrightarrow c_1^*\lor \lor c_2^*$
\item $l_1\lor c_1^*\lor c_2^*$
\end{itemize}

We can even replace the equivalent C-to-F statement after using the equivalence using De Morgan's Laws:
\begin{itemize}
\item $R\Leftrightarrow l_1$
\item $R\Leftrightarrow \lor l_1\lor \lor c_2^*$
\end{itemize}

I hope this answers your question.

On the other hand, it is true in the logical sense: A implies B.

A is (as you said) logically equivalent to the sentence If it rains , then the grass is wet.
B is, on the same logic and in the opposite direction, logically equivalent to the sentence If it does not rain, then the grass is not wet.

Solution:

Let the lengths of the two legs be 5x and 12x, respectively. By the Pythagorean theorem, we have

13^2 = (5x)^2 + (12x)^2

169 = 25x^2 + 144x^2

169 = 169x^2

x^2 = 1

x = 1 or x = -1

Answer: Clang optimizations are \em{very} limited under Linux. You have the `-O3` flag with `-fprofile-instr-Generate` and `-fprofile-force`. These can actually be used with any C++ compiler, but they are only really useful with gcc.

\begin{blockquote}
`-O3` - Enable all optimization and run-time code generation features
of the compiler to produce highly optimized code. The optimizations
may have a significant impact on size of the program. This is the
default setting for both GCC and g++.
\end{blockquote}

`-fprofile-instr-Generate`

\begin{blockquote}
`-fprofile-instr-Generate` - Generate instructions to fill a profile data collection table. Profile instrumentation
uses a table of function profiles and a call site sampling routine.
\end{blockquote}

`-fprofile-force`

\begin{blockquote}
`-fprofile-force` - Force profiling during link
\end{blockquote}

There is no \begin{code}
-f<something>
\end{code} flag with clang, but there are equivalent flags.

You can compile with `-O3 -g` and use `-fprofile-fatal-errors` from `gcc`, which will give better coverage. You might even be able to compile with `-O3 -fno-profile-use` or `--param profile-use=no`. If clang doesn't support this, try compiling with `-O3 -rdynamic` to see if that gives better coverage. The only other option with clang is `-fprofile-fatal-errors` like with gcc. [Both `gcc` and `clang` have the `optimization` and `debugging` sections in their manuals that document `f` flags that affect either option.](https://www.gnu.org/software/binutils/manual/binutils-2.35-man.html#binutils-2.35-man)

If you don't want to manually profile, then you can use the GCC profiling code to make `-rdynamic` with clang's `Clang++` tool instead of using `-fprofile-fatal-errors`. This is what `-lpg` (libprofgecko) actually does.

Also, be careful of using clang++ over plain clang because there have been bugs in the way clang behaves with the C++ language. [The clang++ implementation of C++ is a bit behind the rest of the front-end.](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3855621/why-is-clang-not-as-fast-as-gcc)
